snippet.textDisplay: Painter dude is way chill, not from smokin weed as a few folks commented. Maybe chill from suckin pain fumes for 40 years without a respirator. But he has mad skills, thinned his paint... in the can... measuring by calibrated eyes (not really, kinda sorta, he added thinner and mixed until it flowed off the paint stick right, sooo, yeah, calibrated eyes work) he poured from can directly to gun with no strainer and a lit cigarette in his hand, blew color on that big ass truck, using a 5 year old harbor freight, 1.4 needle, HPLV gravity feed gun, no inline pressure regulator, moisture/contamination filter at the gun, with at least 100 feet of air hose with standard couplers, not high flow couplers, blew a single stage dark color paint on a dark surface base on the cab and a white gel coat on the hood, without a dark primer on the hood AND color matched it without the hood being a half tone (shade) lighter, 3 coats normally sprayed with single stage, with the 15-20 minute setup, between coat, tac time, he continued to shoot and move while mentally keeping track of his coat dry times with a textbook spray technique! And like I said, this was a big ass truck to get around, painters know what I mean. So yeah, he got game, he brought his A game! Sprayer Dude, come to Oklahoma and paint my new desert race truck, it is lightning pearl blue, I have Eastwood HPLV guns, a couple ole siphon sprayers even a new airless, but I’ll go buy you a new harbor freight HPLV gun, with assorted tip sizes and two cartons of smokes. I’ll remove the inline pressure regulators, filters and put standard line couplers back on if you want. Hell, I’ll even hide the mixing cups, strainers and spray gun holders! He probably will have the same results with enough rattle cans!

snippet.textDisplay: it's looking nice westen. some advice from a veteran truck driver. get rid of the accessory side marker lights. put mufflers back on the truck. unless you like getting strait pipe headaches. and you will want take the fuse panel loose and the the housing and wires in the back of it. guys were over loading the panel with after market accessory lights. under the cab you will want to look at the aluminum clutch pedal adjuster shaft. after a while the stress from using the clutch pedal pulls the threads and it simply falls off. you'll never see that coming. some better advice. don't pre-select  the range selector for 5 or 6 gear in the low side.
